g budgets, when public health departments have eliminated tens of thousands of jobs, some argue that a lower-profile and ineffective surgeon general is a waste of money. By tracing stories of how surgeons general like Luther Terry, C. Everett Koop, and Joycelyn Elders created policies and confronted controversy in response to issues like smoking, AIDS, and masturbation, Stobbe highlights how this office is key to shaping the nation’s health and explailns why its decline is harming our national well-being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aExecutives. 0aPhysicianszUnited States. 0aPhysicians. 0aPolitics, Practical. 0aPublic health administrationzUnited States. 0aPublic health administration. 0aScience. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aaids.  aamerican government.  aamerican politics.  acdc.  acenters for disease control and prevention.  adepartment of health and human services.  adoctors.  afederal government.  agovernment and governing.  aleadership.  amasturbation.  anational well being.  aphysicians.  apolitics.  apublic health policy.  apublic health programs.  apublic health service.  asmoking.  asurgeon general of the united states.  asurgeon general.  aunited states of america.  aus public health service commissioned corps.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027229340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095839540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958395423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958395/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY